  <subsection>
    <title>Graphing Transformations of Sine and Cosine</title>
    <p>
      Now that we've become familiar with the sine and cosine graphs, let's apply algebraic graphing techniques to these functions. Recall that when <m>D gt 0</m>, the graph of <m>y = f(x) + D</m> shifts the graph of <m>y = f(x)</m> upward by <m>D</m> units, and the graph of <m>y = f(x) - D</m> shifts the graph of <m>y = f(x)</m> downward by <m>D</m> units.
    </p>
    <definition>
      <title>Vertical Shift</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          The graphs of the functions
        </p>
        <p>
          <me>
            y=\sin x+D \quad \mbox{and } \quad y=\cos x+D
          </me>
        </p>
        <p>
          represent an <term>upward vertical shift</term><idx><h>vertical shift</h></idx> of the graphs <m>y = \sin(x)</m> and <m>y = \cos(x)</m> by <m>D</m> units, respectively.
        </p>
        <p>
          Similarly, the functions
        </p>
        <p>
          <me>
            y=\sin x-D \quad \mbox{and } \quad y=\cos x-D
          </me>
        </p>
        <p>
          depict the graphs of <m>y = \sin(x)</m> and <m>y = \cos(x)</m> with a <term>downward vertical shift</term> by <m>D</m> units, respectively.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>
    <example>
      <title>Vertical Shifts</title>
      <statement>
        <p>Graph each function</p>
        <p>
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p><m>y=\sin(x)+2</m></p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p><m>y=\cos(x)-1</m></p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          <ol>
            <li>
              <figure xml:id="sin-vshift">
                <caption>The graph of <m>y=\sin(x)+2</m> is the same as the graph of <m>y=\sin(x)</m> but shifted up by 2 units.</caption>
                <image xml:id="fig-sin-vshift">
                  <latex-image>
                    \begin{tikzpicture}
                    \begin{axis}[
                    axis lines=middle,clip=false,
                    xmin=-2*pi-0.5,xmax=3*pi+0.5,ymin=-1.2,ymax=3.2,
                    ytick={-1,1,2,3},
                    minor ytick={-0.5,0.5,1.5,2.5},
                    xtick={-2*pi,-pi,0,pi,2*pi,3*pi},
                    xticklabels={\(-2\pi\),\(-\pi\),\(0\),\(\pi\),\(2\pi\),\(3\pi\)},
                    xticklabel style={black},
                    xlabel=\(x\),
                    ylabel=\(y\)]
                    \addplot[stealth-stealth,domain=-2*pi-0.5:3*pi+0.5,samples=200,blue,line width=1pt]{sin(deg(x))}node[right,pos=1]{\(y=\sin x\)};
                    \addplot[stealth-stealth,domain=-2*pi-0.5:3*pi+0.5,samples=200,red,line width=1pt]{2+sin(deg(x))}node[right,pos=1]{\(y=\sin(x)+2\)};
                    \addplot [dashed,red,fill=red!90!black,opacity=0.5] coordinates {(-2*pi,2) (3*pi,2)};
                    \end{axis}
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                  </latex-image>
                </image>
              </figure>
            </li>
            <li>
              <figure xml:id="cos-vshift">
                <caption>The graph of <m>y=\cos(x)-1</m> is the same as the graph of <m>y=\cos(x)</m> but shifted down by 1 unit.</caption>
                <image xml:id="fig-cos-vshift">
                  <latex-image>
                    \begin{tikzpicture}
                    \begin{axis}[
                    axis lines=middle,clip=false,
                    xmin=-2*pi-0.5,xmax=3*pi+0.5,ymin=-2.2,ymax=1.2,
                    ytick={-2,-1,1},
                    minor ytick={-1.5,-0.5,0.5},
                    xtick={-2*pi,-pi,0,pi,2*pi,3*pi},
                    xticklabels={\(-2\pi\),\(-\pi\),\(0\),\(\pi\),\(2\pi\),\(3\pi\)},
                    xticklabel style={black},
                    xlabel=\(x\),
                    ylabel=\(y\)]
                    \addplot[stealth-stealth,domain=-2*pi-0.5:3*pi+0.5,samples=200,blue,line width=1pt]{cos(deg(x))}node[right,pos=1]{\(y=\cos x\)};
                    \addplot[stealth-stealth,domain=-2*pi-0.5:3*pi+0.5,samples=200,red,line width=1pt]{-1+cos(deg(x))}node[right,pos=1]{\(y=\cos(x)-1\)};
                    \addplot [dashed,red,fill=red!90!black,opacity=0.5] coordinates {(-2*pi,-1) (3*pi,-1)};
                    \end{axis}
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                  </latex-image>
                </image>
              </figure>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
    <p>
      Additionally, remember that the graph <m>y = -f(x)</m> reflects the graph of <m>y = f(x)</m> about the <m>x</m>-axis.
    </p>
    <definition>
      <title>Reflection about the <m>x</m>-axis</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          The functions
        </p>
        <p>
          <me>
            y=-\sin x \quad \mbox{and} \quad y=-\cos x
          </me>
        </p>
        <p>
          represent the graphs of <m>y = \sin(x)</m> and <m>y = \cos(x)</m> with a <term>reflection</term><idx><h>reflection</h><h>about <m>x</m>-axis</h></idx> about the <m>x</m>-axis, respectively.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>
    <example>
      <title>Reflections about the <m>x</m>-axis</title>
      <statement>
        <p>Graph <m>y=-\sin(x)</m></p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <figure xml:id="sin-x-axis-reflect">
          <caption>The graph <m>y = -\sin(x)</m> is obtained by multiplying every <m>y-</m>value of the <m>y = \sin(x)</m> graph by <m>-1</m>. This transformation reflects all points across the x-axis, turning positive values negative and negative values positive. As a result, the graph of <m>y = -\sin(x)</m> is the reflection of <m>y = \sin(x)</m> about the x-axis.</caption>
          <image xml:id="fig-sin-x-axis-reflect">
            <latex-image>
              \begin{tikzpicture}
              \begin{axis}[
              axis lines=middle,clip=false,
              xmin=-2*pi-0.5,xmax=3*pi+0.5,ymin=-1.2,ymax=1.2,
              ytick={-1,1},
              minor ytick={-0.5,0.5,1.5,2.5},
              xtick={-2*pi,-pi,0,pi,2*pi,3*pi},
              xticklabels={\(-2\pi\),\(-\pi\),\(0\),\(\pi\),\(2\pi\),\(3\pi\)},
              xticklabel style={black},
              xlabel=\(x\),
              ylabel=\(y\)]
              \addplot[stealth-stealth,domain=-2*pi-0.5:3*pi+0.5,samples=200,blue,line width=1pt]{sin(deg(x))}node[right,pos=1]{\(y=\sin x\)};
              \addplot[stealth-stealth,domain=-2*pi-0.5:3*pi+0.5,samples=200,red,line width=1pt]{-sin(deg(x))}node[right,pos=1]{\(y=-\sin(x)\)};
              \end{axis}
              \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
          </image>
        </figure>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <example xml:id="ex_vert-stretch-compression">
      <title>Vertical Stretches and Compressions</title>
      <statement>
        <p>Graph each function</p>
        <p>
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p><m>y=2\cos(x)</m></p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p><m>y=\frac{1}{2}\cos(x)</m></p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <figure xml:id="cos-amplitudes">
          <caption>The graph of <m>y = 2\cos(x)</m> is achieved by vertically stretching the <m>y</m>-values of <m>y = \cos(x)</m> by a factor of 2. Similarly, the graph of <m>y = \frac{1}{2}\cos(x)</m> is obtained by vertically compressing the <m>y</m>-values of <m>y = \cos(x)</m> by a factor of <m>\frac{1}{2}</m>.</caption>
          <image xml:id="fig-cos-amplitudes">
            <latex-image>
              \begin{tikzpicture}
              \begin{axis}[
              axis lines=middle,clip=false,
              xmin=-2*pi-0.5,xmax=3*pi+0.5,ymin=-2.2,ymax=2.2,
              ytick={-2,-1,1,2},
              minor ytick={-1.5,-0.5,0.5,1.5},
              xtick={-2*pi,-pi,0,pi,2*pi,3*pi},
              xticklabels={\(-2\pi\),\(-\pi\),\(0\),\(\pi\),\(2\pi\),\(3\pi\)},
              xticklabel style={black},
              xlabel=\(x\),
              ylabel=\(y\)]
              \addplot[stealth-stealth,domain=-2*pi-0.5:3*pi+0.5,samples=200,blue,line width=1pt]{cos(deg(x))}node[right,pos=1]{\(y=\cos x\)};
              \addplot[stealth-stealth,domain=-2*pi-0.5:3*pi+0.5,samples=200,red,line width=1pt]{2*cos(deg(x))}node[right,pos=1]{\(y=2\cos x\)};
              \addplot[stealth-stealth,domain=-2*pi-0.5:3*pi+0.5,samples=200,orange,line width=1pt]{0.5*cos(deg(x))}node[right,pos=1]{\(y=\frac{1}{2}\cos x\)};
              \end{axis}
              \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
          </image>
        </figure>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <p>
      The factor multiplied at the front of the cosine function plays a crucial role in stretching and compressing the graph. This factor is known as the <term>amplitude</term>, measuring the maximum vertical distance from the midline to the peak or trough of a sinusoidal wave. In <xref ref="ex_vert-stretch-compression">Example</xref>, the amplitude of <m>y=2\cos(x)</m> is 2, indicating a <term>vertical stretch</term><idx><h>vertical stretch</h></idx> by a factor of 2 compared to the standard cosine function. Conversely, for <m>y=\frac{1}{2}\cos(x)</m>, the amplitude is <m>\frac{1}{2}</m>, which represented a <term>vertical compression</term><idx><h>vertical compression</h></idx> by a factor of <m>\frac{1}{2}</m>.
    </p>

    <definition>
      <title>Amplitude</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>f</m> be a periodic function with <m>M</m> and <m>N</m> as the maximum and minimum values, respectively. The <term>amplitude</term>,<idx><h>amplitude</h></idx> of <m>f</m> is defined as
        </p>
        <p>
          <me>
            \frac{M-N}{2}.
          </me>
        </p>
        <p>
          The amplitude can be thought of as the height of the function, representing half the distance between its maximum and minimum values. For a graph centered about the <m>x</m>-axis, the amplitude is simply the maximum value of <m>f</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          In general, for
        </p>
        <p>
          <me>y = A \cdot \sin(x) \quad \mbox{or} \quad y= A \cdot \cos(x)</me>
        </p>
        <p>
          the amplitude is given by the absolute value of <m>A</m>, denoted as
        </p>
        <p>
          <me>
            \mbox{amplitude}=|A|.
          </me>
        </p>
        <p>
          This absolute value ensures that amplitude is always a positive value, representing the magnitude of the vertical stretching or compression.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>
    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>Graph <m>y=-4\sin x</m></p> and identify the amplitude.
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          The amplitude is <m>|-4|=4</m>.
        </p>
        <figure xml:id="sin-amplitudes">
          <caption>Since the amplitude of <m>y = -4\sin(x)</m> is <m>4</m>, the graph is stretched by a factor of 4 and will oscillate between <m>-4</m> and <m>4</m>. Additionally, the negative sign indicates that the graph is reflected about the <m>x</m>-axis.
          </caption>
          <image xml:id="fig-sin-amplitudes">
            <latex-image>
              \begin{tikzpicture}
              \begin{axis}[
              axis lines=middle,clip=false,
              xmin=-2*pi-0.5,xmax=3*pi+0.5,ymin=-4.2,ymax=4.2,
              ytick={-4,-3-2,-1,1,2,3,4},
              minor ytick={-3.5,-2.5,-1.5,-0.5,0.5,1.5,2.5,3.5},
              xtick={-2*pi,-pi,0,pi,2*pi,3*pi},
              xticklabels={\(-2\pi\),\(-\pi\),\(0\),\(\pi\),\(2\pi\),\(3\pi\)},
              xticklabel style={black},
              xlabel=\(x\),
              ylabel=\(y\)]
              \addplot[stealth-stealth,domain=-2*pi-0.5:3*pi+0.5,samples=200,blue,line width=1pt]{sin(deg(x))}node[right,pos=1]{\(y=\sin x\)};
              \addplot[stealth-stealth,domain=-2*pi-0.5:3*pi+0.5,samples=200,red,line width=1pt]{-4*sin(deg(x))}node[right,pos=1]{\(y=-4\sin x\)};
              \end{axis}
              \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
          </image>
        </figure>
      </solution>
    </example>
    <p>
      Next we will look at functions of the form
    </p>
    <p>
      <me>
        y=\sin Bx \quad \mbox{and} \quad y=\cos Bx
      </me>
    </p>
    <p>
      where we assume <m>B\gt0</m>. You may recall from algebra that for functions of the form <m>y=f(Bx)</m>, a key factor emerges: when <m>B \gt 1</m>, the graph undergoes horizontal compression by a factor of <m>\frac{1}{B}</m>; conversely, when <m>0 \lt B \lt 1</m>, the graph is horizontally stretched by a factor of <m>\frac{1}{B}</m>. Given that sine and cosine complete one period in <m>2\pi</m>, the horizontal stretching or compressing of a period will be by a factor of <m>\frac{1}{B}</m>.
    </p>
    <definition>
      <title>Period</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          For sine and cosine functions of the form
        </p>
        <p>
          <me>
            y=\sin Bx \quad \mbox{and} \quad y=\cos Bx \quad (\mbox{assume }B\gt 0)
          </me>
        </p>
        <p>
          the <term>period</term><idx><h>period</h></idx> is defined as
        </p>
        <p>
          <me>
            \mbox{period}=\frac{2\pi}{B}
          </me>
        </p>
        <p>
          Thus, if <m>B\gt 1</m>, the period is compressed; if <m>0\lt B\lt 1</m>, the period is stretched.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>
    
    <example>
      <title>Horizontal Stretches and Compressions</title>
      <statement>
        <p>Identify the period and graph one period for each of the following functions:</p>
        <p>
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p><m>y=\sin(2x)</m></p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p><m>y=\sin\left(\frac{1}{2}x\right)</m></p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p><m>y=\sin\left(\frac{1}{3}x\right)</m></p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                The period for <m>y=\sin(2x)</m> is
              </p>
              <p>
                <me>
                  \mbox{period}=\frac{2\pi}{2}=\pi
                </me>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                The period for <m>y=\sin\left(\frac{1}{2}x\right)</m> is
              </p>
              <p>
                <me>
                  \mbox{period}=\frac{2\pi}{\frac{1}{2}}=2\pi\cdot\frac{2}{1}=4\pi
                </me>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                The period for <m>y=\sin\left(\frac{1}{3}x\right)</m> is
              </p>
              <p>
                <me>
                  \mbox{period}=\frac{2\pi}{\frac{1}{3}}=2\pi\cdot\frac{3}{1}=6\pi
                </me>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
        <figure xml:id="sin-period">
          <caption>One period each of <m>y=\sin(2x)</m>, <m>y=\sin\left(\frac{1}{2}x\right)</m>, and <m>y=\sin\left(\frac{1}{3}x\right)</m> compared to the standard <m>y=\sin(x)</m> graph. Observe the distinct effects of horizontal compression (when <m>B=2</m>, reducing the period to <m>\frac{\pi}{2}</m>) and stretching (when <m>B=\frac{1}{2}</m> and <m>B=\frac{1}{3}</m>, increasing the period to <m>4\pi</m> and <m>6\pi</m>, respectively).</caption>
          <image xml:id="fig-sin-period">
            <latex-image>
              \begin{tikzpicture}
              \begin{axis}[
              axis lines=middle,clip=false,
              xmin=-0.5,xmax=6*pi+0.5,ymin=-2.2,ymax=2.2,
              ytick={-1,1},
              minor ytick={-0.5,0.5},
              xtick={0,pi,2*pi,3*pi,4*pi,5*pi,6*pi},
              xticklabels={\(0\),\(\pi\),\(2\pi\),\(3\pi\),\(4\pi\),\(5\pi\),\(6\pi\)},
              xticklabel style={black},
              xlabel=\(x\),
              ylabel=\(y\)]
              \addplot[domain=0:2*pi,samples=200,blue,line width=1pt]{sin(deg(x))}node[above,pos=0.25]{\(y=\sin x\)};
              \addplot[domain=0:pi,samples=200,red,line width=1pt]{sin(deg(2*x))}node[below,pos=0.75]{\(y=\sin 2x\)};
              \addplot[domain=0:4*pi,samples=200,purple,line width=1pt]{sin(deg(x/2))}node[below,pos=0.75]{\(y=\sin \frac{1}{2}x\)};
              \addplot[domain=0:6*pi,samples=200,orange,line width=1pt]{sin(deg(x/3))}node[below,pos=0.75]{\(y=\sin \frac{1}{3}x\)};
              \end{axis}
              \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
          </image>
        </figure>
            

      </solution>
    </example>


